On @realmoney It's A "Five"! * What's wrong with rolling a 2.40% three month Treasury bill given the market action and fundamental uncertainties? * A Bull Market in complacency, in hyperbole and in hopium. * More evidence of a topping process. * Remember, buyers live higher and

sellers live lower. "Two in the fairway, three (no four) in the bunker, over the green, on to the green, two putts. It's a "5"! - Bill Murray, TV Advertisement ispot.tv/ad/Ic2F/golf-channe… Though today certainly does not make a market's full life cycle, there is more evidence that

the overall market is rolling over - possibly substantiating the notion that a major market top is in the process of being formed. LINK TO OPENER The damage in certain sectors belies a 2850 S&P Index. As an example, remember the near unanimity on semiconductors two months ago -

with Micron (a Tepper Tout, among other hedge hoggers), Nvidia and Intel having been the stocks du jour by those parade in the business media? Crickets now - with certainly no admission of guilt. Or a recommended Apple that traded at $217 post earnings and is now at $183 (-$6

only 20 days ago). Remember the trade talk bulls who thought the negotiation would be brief an successful, or that the damage would be diminimous? Crickets, there too. We are in a Bull Market in complacency, in hyperbole and in hopium. As witness I again just heard from someone

in the business media that we have a "Trump Put" regarding the Chinese trade negotiation. Some have posited that the negotiations (like those with North Korea et al) are just posturing. I couldn't disagree more. If this decline continues we will not likely hear about the near

universal bullishness of the last few months, as false narratives realmoney.thestreet.com/doug… and revisionism will be the continuing order of the day. Today's low lites: * Breadth is nearly 2-1 negative.(1100 advancers, 1759 decliners) * Though we have had the customary rally off

of the lows, the advance is unimpressive to this observer. * QQQs under SSSs. * The shares of basic industrials and materials have no life whatsoever. * A new low in Deutsche Bank shares. (I have spent two years discussing the woeful state of DB and the European bank industry)

* More weak high frequency economic data Finally, in a world dominated by ETFs and a plethora of products that worship at the altar of price momentum (and though it is counter intuitive) - buyers live higher and sellers live lower. So, if the recent weakness, those many that

lie on the same side of the (bullish) boat, could be selling at lower levels in the weeks ahead. In that case, being (bearish and) anticipatory may pay off over the balance of the Summer. As Divine Ms M writes, "Price has a way of changing sentiment." @tomkeene @SquawkCNBC
